growing scholarly push to situate American studies within the broader context of the American hemisphere.This book examines poets and artists in the Americas during the late twentieth and early twenty-first centuries to show how they worked to make language into material objects and material objects into language. It builds a theory of ‘material poetics’ that provides an alternative account of poetry in hemispheric America. Rebecca Kosick argues that by reframing American poetry to prominently include object-oriented practices within and beyond the United States, material poetry can be seen as representing a significant branch of the American poetic tradition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aAmerican poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican poetryy21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLatin American literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aLatin American poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLatin American poetryy21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMaterialism in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aART / Art & Politics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z97831107804130 cprintz978147447460340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147447462740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474474627423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474474627/original  a978-3-11-078041-3  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK